Title: Veggie Tales: Veggies In Space

reviewText: Since watching "Where's God When I'm Scared?!", I never quit liking VeggieTales, and in my brain's library of favorite cartoons, only Pixar flicks come second! The problem is that some of the vegetable tales from this last decade have been re-writes of stories, and weren't as fresh and funny as they once were.But THIS film brings back the old silliness, originality, and what makes VeggieTales fun! From the reprise of the "U.S.S. Applepies" (from "Are You My Neighbor?") and the popcorn meteorites, to when the gourds' robot in sumo mode was fighting with underwear on a moon, to when the Applepies used "1.25 gigglewatts" with an electric hand, this was absolutely funny! There's plenty of tidbits for the nostalgic, including the "Pizza Angel" pizzas in the credits (though no lion pizzas, though!) And if you like sci-fi, parodies on 2001: A Space Odyssey, Star Wars, Star Trek, and more are there for the spotting throughout the 48-minute movie!The songs were great! Catchy, modern, and downright funny--such as the Asteroid Cowboys song--it really reveals that the veggies are still very much ready for action, and I think will be great to show to kids, whether at home or in a church setting. Some scenes, like ropes coming down when the "beamer" didn't work, and when popcorn burned a lock, were honestly hilarious, and it was nice to see a new type of veggie tale.There's only one thing I think I'd almost remove one star for, though: While the morals were there, and it was all about sharing, outside of Qwerty's usual verse, there really wasn't a reason that the audience could get without watching the movie. Sharing has been a theme in "Lyle: The Kindly Viking" and others, and I wished a new theme could have been in this one. There have been people who've mentioned VeggieTales isn't Christian... and I would say to watch "An Easter Carol" with the scene where Hope sings or just look at the Bible verses, and so in that area I disagree... but I still do wish there was a new theme. I know after _years_ of films it must be challenging for the team, but despite that, if I could say one last thing: this work definitely shows that the veggies are still alive and fresh as ever!
Title: Veggie Tales: Veggies In Space

reviewText: Think Veggietales meets Star Wars/ Star Trek (it reminds me of both.)  This is a cute DVD that is all about working together, sharing, friendship and other great lessons for kids.  It is a cute story that you can't help but laugh and smile at because it stars talking vegetables as the characters.  The songs are cute and I've heard my kids singing them randomly throughout the day.  We enjoyed this movie and have watched it a few times already!
Title: Veggie Tales: Veggies In Space

reviewText: "Veggies in Space: The Fennel Frontier" is another wonderful Veggie-parody of popular media in a long line of other Veggie videos (including "The Ballad of Little Joe", "It's A Meaningful Life", "The Wonderful Wizard of Ha's", and "Lord of the Beans").  This time we have the return of the USS Applepies (first seen in 1995's "Are You My Neighbor?"), but with even more overt references to Star Trek as Bob and Larry are now in the roles of Captain Cuke and his first officer, Mr. Spork.In the video,  Capt Cuke, Mr. Spork and the rest of the crew of the USS Applepies are sent on a mission to stop the evil space pirate, Luntar the Looter (protrayed by Mr. Lunt).  However, Cuke & Spork, posing undercover as "Tootany" tourists, find that Luntar is himself a victim, desperately trying to save his planet from solar burst popcorn meteorites.  When Luntar's nephew decides to share his lunch with the captured Applepies crew, he gives Capt Cuke the idea that the Galactic Law of Finder's Keepers may not be all its cracked up to be.  The video's theme is the power of sharing.
summary: The Return of the USS Applepies!!!
Title: Veggie Tales: Veggies In Space

reviewText: The kids LOVED it. We're huge Veggie fans, and this ranked on the kiddo's top 5 all time faves. It's one they'll watch again and again.
